Data Analysis Recipe Site Traffic¶

1. Data Validation¶

Describe validation and cleaning steps for every column in the data

1.1 Information about the Data:¶

recipe - Nominal. This field serves as a unique identifier for each recipe. It is not possible to have missing values for this field due to the structure of the database.

calories - Discrete. Represents the calorie count of a recipe. In case of missing values, the mean value of the specified category is used for filling.

carbohydrate - Discrete. Indicates the quantity of carbohydrates in grams in a recipe. Missing values are imputed with the mean value of the designated category.

sugar - Discrete. Denotes the amount of sugar in grams present in a recipe. Missing values are replaced with the computed mean value of the relevant category.

protein - Discrete. Represents the protein content in grams of a recipe. If values are missing, they are substituted with the mean value of the specified category.

category - Nominal. This field categorizes recipes into ten distinct groups, denoted by descriptive names. The original names have been substituted with corresponding names.

servings - Discrete. Signifies the number of servings a recipe is intended to provide.

high_traffic - Nominal. Describes the level of traffic with two possible values: "High" and "Null". Instances where the value was "Null" have been replaced with "Low".

# Data Validation:
# recipe. Numeric, unique identifier of recipe. 

# Calculate the mean of each category for the specified columns
mean_values = df_recipe.groupby('category')['calories', 'protein', 'sugar', 'carbohydrate'].transform('mean')

# Fill the missing values in the specified columns with the computed mean values
df_recipe[['calories', 'protein', 'sugar', 'carbohydrate']] = df_recipe[['calories', 'protein', 'sugar', 'carbohydrate']].fillna(mean_values)

# category Character, type of recipe. Recipes are listed in one of ten possible groupings ('Lunch/Snacks', 'Beverages', 'Potato', 'Vegetable', 'Meat', 'Chicken', 'Pork', 'Dessert', 'Breakfast', 'One Dish Meal').
df_recipe['category'] = df_recipe['category'].replace({'Chicken Breast':'Chicken'})

# servings Numeric, number of servings for the recipe.
df_recipe['servings'] = df_recipe['servings'].replace({'4 as a snack': '4', '6 as a snack': '6'}).astype(str).fillna(0).astype(float)

# high_traffic Character, if the traffic to the site was high when this recipe was shown, this is marked with “High”.
df_recipe['high_traffic'] = df_recipe['high_traffic'].fillna(0).replace(0, 'Low')

# Order Categories
ordered_cats = {"category":['Lunch/Snacks', 'Beverages', 'Potato', 'Vegetable', 'Meat', 'Chicken', 'Pork', 'Dessert', 'Breakfast', 'One Dish Meal'],
               "high_traffic": ['High', 'Low']}

df_recipe['category'].sort_values()

# Loop through DataFrame columns to efficiently change data types
for col in df_recipe:
    
    # Convert integer columns to int32
    if df_recipe[col].dtype == 'int':
        df_recipe[col] = df_recipe[col].astype('int16')
    
    # Convert float columns to float16
    elif df_recipe[col].dtype == 'float':
        df_recipe[col] = df_recipe[col].astype('float16')
        
    #elif df_fitness_clean[col].dtype == 'bool':
        #df_recipe[col] = df_recipe[col].astype('bool')
    
    # Convert columns containing ordered categorical data to ordered categories using dict
    elif col in ordered_cats.keys():
        category = pd.CategoricalDtype(ordered_cats[col], ordered=True)
        df_recipe[col] = df_recipe[col].astype(category)
        
    # Convert remaining columns to standard categories
    else:
        df_recipe[col] = df_recipe[col].astype('category')

# Drop rows with 'High' and 'Low' traffic
df_recipe_high_traffic = df_recipe[df_recipe['high_traffic'] == 'High'].copy()
df_recipe_low_traffic = df_recipe[df_recipe['high_traffic'] == 'Low'].copy()

2. Exploratory Analysis¶

Include two different graphics showing single variables only to demonstrate the characteristics of data. Include at least one graphic showing two or more variables to represent the relationship between features. Describe your findings.

The following highlight the complex interplay between category popularity, user engagement, and different traffic levels. The insights can guide content strategies, helping creators adapt their content based on the performance of different categories across varying traffic conditions.

2.1 Categories with "High" Traffic¶

The graph shows how many people visit different recipe categories on the website. This helps us decide which recipes to focus on and which ones people like the most.

2.1.1 High Traffic Categories:¶

Potato, Vegetable, and Pork are popular with 14.5%, 14.3%, and 13.4% of recipes respectively. These categories are relatively popular in both high and low traffic, suggesting that they attract consistent attention regardless of traffic levels.

Chicken contribute to 12.7% of high traffic recipesit, also appears in a significant number of low traffic recipes (17.2%), indicating that its popularity doesn't guarantee consistent engagement.

Meat, Dessert, and One Dish Meal each represent around 10% of high traffic recipes. Breakfast and Beverages have comparatively lower popularity, with 5.7% and 0.9% respectively.

2.1.2 Low Traffic Categories:¶

Potato, Pork, and Chicken are rarely found with 0.9%, 0.2%, and 17.2% of low traffic recipes respectively. Breakfast, Beverages, and Lunch/Snacks are also less common, making up 12.7%, 15.2%, and 5.6% respectively. Dessert, One Dish Meal, and Meat have moderate representation with around 8% each. Vegetable stands out as the least common, accounting for only 0.2% of low traffic recipes. These insights provide a clear view of how different categories perform in terms of both the number of recipes and their distribution in 'High Traffic' and 'Low Traffic' categories.

# Define the desired order of categories
desired_order = ['Potato', 'Vegetable', 'Pork', 'Chicken', 'Meat', 'Lunch/Snacks', 'Dessert', 'One Dish Meal', 'Breakfast', 'Beverages']

# Calculate the frequency of counts for each category
traffic_counts = df_recipe_high_traffic['category'].value_counts().reindex(desired_order, fill_value=0)
traffic_counts_low = df_recipe_low_traffic['category'].value_counts().reindex(desired_order, fill_value=0)

# Calculate the percentage of counts for each category
percentage_counts = traffic_counts / len(df_recipe_high_traffic) * 100
percentage_counts_low = traffic_counts_low / len(df_recipe_high_traffic) * 100

# Create bar plots for both high and low traffic by category
traffic_counts_high = df_recipe_high_traffic['category'].value_counts().loc[desired_order]
traffic_counts_low = df_recipe_low_traffic['category'].value_counts().loc[desired_order]

# Create a horizontal bar plot to show the number of different categories with high and low traffic
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))
plt.suptitle('Graph 1-1 Number of Different Categories with High and Low Traffic', fontsize=20)

# Create a horizontal bar plot to show the number of different categories with high traffic
sns.barplot(ax=axes[0], x=traffic_counts.values, y=traffic_counts.index, label='Frequency (High Traffic)', color='blue', alpha=0.7, order=desired_order)
# Display traffic counts on top of the bars for high traffic
for index, value in enumerate(traffic_counts_high.values):
    axes[0].text(value + 1, index, str(value), va='center', color='blue', fontsize=10)  # Display on top of blue bars
axes[0].set_title("Number of Different Categories with 'High Traffic'")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Frequency")
axes[0].set_ylabel("Category")
axes[0].legend()

# Create a horizontal bar plot to show the number of different categories with low traffic (underneath the high traffic bars)
sns.barplot(ax=axes[1], x=traffic_counts_low.values, y=traffic_counts_low.index, label='Frequency (Low Traffic)', color='red', alpha=0.7, order=desired_order)
# Display traffic counts on top of the bars for low traffic
for index, value in enumerate(traffic_counts_low.values):
    axes[1].text(value + 1, index, str(value), va='center', color='red', fontsize=10)  # Display on top of red bars
axes[1].set_title("Number of Different Categories with 'Low Traffic'")
axes[1].set_xlabel("Frequency")
axes[1].set_ylabel("Category")
axes[1].legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

2.2 Numbers of Servings per Category¶

We examine the relationship between the 'servings' and 'category' variables, using a graphical representation where the bars are color-coded and styled based on the 'servings' number. This visualization enables us to easily identify categories with a notable abundance of recipes for each serving size.

Specifically, The Graph 1-5 visualizes the distribution of recipes for each chosen "Portion" value across various categories. This graph provides insights into the quantity of recipes in the "Vegetable," "Potato," "Pork," and "Chicken" categories that correspond to different selected "Serving" values. Notably, this visualization highlights that the categories with the highest recipe counts are those with around four servings. Furthermore, the "Breakfast" and "Lunch/Snack" categories exhibit a comparable distribution pattern.

    df_recipe_high_traffic = df_recipe_high_traffic.loc[(df_recipe_high_traffic[column] >= lower) & (df_recipe_high_traffic[column] <= upper)]

The selection was driven by their appropriateness for binary classification tasks and their potential to grasp intricate patterns within the data.

Our objective involves predicting whether a recipe will generate high traffic, leveraging a range of features encompassing servings, nutritional composition, and category classification.

These metrics illuminate the effectiveness of the models in accurately and erroneously forecasting various categories based on the actual labels. From these metrics, we extract precision, recall, and F1-score, furnishing deeper insights into the models' performance.

4. Model Evaluation¶

Describe the performance of the two models based on an appropriate metric.

4.1 Evaluation Metrics:¶

We employ the following values to assess the models' performance:

True Positive (TP): The count of instances accurately predicted as "High" traffic.

True Negative (TN): The count of instances correctly predicted as "Low" traffic.

False Positive (FP): The count of instances inaccurately predicted as "High" traffic when they are actually "Low" traffic.

False Negative (FN): The count of instances inaccurately predicted as "Low" traffic when they are actually "High" traffic.

These values form the basis for calculating diverse metrics such as precision, recall, and F1-score. To elaborate:

Precision: The ratio of accurately predicted "High" traffic instances (TP) to the total predicted "High" traffic instances (TP + FP). It gauges the accuracy of predicted "High" traffic instances.

Recall: The ratio of accurately predicted "High" traffic instances (TP) to the total actual "High" traffic instances (TP + FN). It quantifies the model's ability to capture all occurrences of "High" traffic.

F1-score: The harmonic mean of precision and recall. It furnishes a balanced assessment that considers both precision and recall.

These metrics facilitate an evaluation of the model's proficiency in correctly identifying high traffic recipes while minimizing misclassifications.

4.2 Performance Metric:¶

In our evaluation process, we assessed the models using several key metrics, including the ROC AUC score, precision, recall, and F1-score. The ROC AUC score holds particular significance for this task, as it quantifies the model's capability to differentiate effectively between high and low traffic recipes.

6. Final Summary and Recommendations¶

In this study, our goal was to figure out which recipes could attract lots of attention online. We created a basic model using Logistic Regression, and we also made a other model Random Forest - to compare them. We measured how well these models did by looking at accuracy, reports, charts, and other scores. We didn't stop there! We also drew pictures to see which recipe categories had the best chance of being really popular.

6.1 Model Performance:¶

The Logistic Regression model achieved an accuracy of around 0.76. It performed well in precision, recall, and F1-score for both high and low traffic categories. The Random Forest model achieved accuracies of about 0.70, respectively. The model also showed competitive performance in predicting high traffic recipes.

Predicted Probabilities Visualization: We made pictures to show how likely different recipe categories are to get a lot of website visitors. This helped us see which categories have a better chance of being really popular.

Recommendations for the Business, based on all this, here's what we suggest

After considering both the evaluation metrics and business needs, the Logistic Regression model emerges as the top performer. It boasts the highest ROC AUC score and strikes a good balance between precision and recall. This model is the prime choice for deployment.

While the Random Forest and Gradient Boosting models also show promise, they might be suitable alternatives, especially if a slightly higher recall is acceptable even if it comes with a bit lower precision.

In practical terms, it's recommended that the business implements the Logistic Regression model for predicting high traffic recipes. Doing so could lead to more informed decision-making, optimizing recipe selection, and making better use of resources.

By using the Logistic Regression model, the business can make smarter choices about which recipes to focus on. This could lead to more people visiting the website and checking out those recipes. Overall, this analysis gives some solid insights to help the business get more attention and make better decisions.

6.2 Recommendations:¶

Focus on High Traffic Categories: Use the predicted probabilities to pay more attention to recipes in categories with higher chances of getting lots of traffic. People are more likely to be interested in these categories.

Plan Content and Promotion: Check what's special about recipes in those high-traffic categories. Then, create content and promote it in a way that gets people excited about those recipes.

Understand What Matters: Use models like Random Forest and Gradient Boosting to see which parts of a recipe make it popular. This can help make new recipes or improve old ones.

Keep an Eye on Things: Set up a system to keep watching how recipes do and adjust plans if needed. Keep the models updated with new information to make them better over time.

Know Your Users: Look at when users like to cook or what days they visit the most. This info can help suggest recipes they'll enjoy.

Get Help from Experts: Work with bloggers, influencers, or chefs who know a lot about popular recipe categories. They can help get more attention to these recipes.

Ask Users and Test: Get feedback from users who try the recipes in high-traffic categories. Test different versions to see what works best.

Make Users Happy: Think about what users enjoy and like. Make sure the recipes don't just attract attention but also give a good cooking experience.

By following these ideas, the business can make better recipes, engage users more, and get more people to visit the website. This will lead to happier users and a better business overall.
